During his six years in Bristol, chairman Jimmy Pitaro has carefully pivote=
d ESPN away from a network that condones political expression to a business=
-friendly safe space for sports. And he=E2=80=99s not changing his tune now=
=2E

John Ourand ( https://puck.news/john-ourand/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Varsity+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F7%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io )
JOHN OURAND ( https://puck.news/john-ourand/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Varsity+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F7%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io )

On Wednesday morning, a few hours after the AP called the presidential elec=
tion for Trump, ESPN anchor Mike Greenberg opened the network=E2=80=99s mor=
ning show, Get Up, with =E2=80=9Cjust one brief moment of seriousness.=E2=
=80=9D Staring at the camera with what can only be described as an earnest =
expression, and without mentioning either candidate, Greeny outlined his vi=
ew of ESPN=E2=80=99s political philosophy. =E2=80=9CIf you are choosing to =
turn ESPN on your television today, it is because you are begging for a rep=
rieve,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou want someone to talk about football, =
which feels very normal to you. You want someone to make you laugh, which i=
s what we try to do every single day. That=E2=80=99s what we=E2=80=99re goi=
ng to do.=E2=80=9D

When Trump won eight years ago, Bristol was a political hotbed. Several ESP=
Ners across the network decided that they
could not, and would not, remain silent. But six years into Jimmy Pitaro=E2=
=80=99s reign, nobody would accuse the company of being political. After Gr=
eenberg=E2=80=99s monologue, he embarked on a zany recap of the NFL=E2=80=
=99s trade deadline moves. Greenberg=E2=80=99s opening set the tone for all=
 the studio shows that followed: Even First Take=E2=80=99s Stephen A. Smith=
, who is certainly not shy about addressing the wedge issues of the day, ke=
pt his focus on the NFL.

In many respects, Wednesday=E2=80=99s battened-down broadcast represented t=
he culmination of a repositioning strategy that Pitaro implemented when he =
was brought on in the spring of 2018. Back then, the network was defined by=
 a patina of activism in the post-Trump, post-Kaepernick #Resistance era. I=
n 2017, the White House publicly called on ESPN to fire Jemele Hill after t=
he SportsCenter host called Trump a white supremacist on Twitter. Plenty of=
 other on-air talent, including
Dan Le Batard and Pablo Torre, were openly criticizing Trump.

Pitaro wanted to wade into politics only when there was a clear intersectio=
n with sports, like covering athletes and coaches as they engaged in variou=
s political protests. Indeed, for Pitaro, the decision made business sense.=
 He often cited research demonstrating that people of all political persuas=
ions would rather not hear their favorite talking heads yammering about pol=
itics on ESPN. Viewers, he often tells people, see ESPN, and sports writ la=
rge, as an escape from all that. Whether this is actually true is not a set=
tled matter, but it=E2=80=99s undeniable that Pitaro lived up to his words.

Centrism in the McAfee Era

Naturally, Pitaro=E2=80=99s edict hasn=E2=80=99t been hiccup-free. During t=
his election cycle, Stephen A. has appeared on Sean Hannity=E2=80=99s Fox N=
ews show=E2=80=94something that insiders have described as a carve-out for =
one of Bristol=E2=80=99s biggest stars. Pat McAfee has had guests rant and =
rave about political flashpoints on his show, including vaccine provocateur=
 Aaron Rodgers and the so-called comedian Tony Hinchcliffe. (As usual, McAf=
ee seems to operate according to his own rules, and the executives in Brist=
ol placate him, as the Norby Williamson defenestration attested.) A couple =
of years ago, ESPN announcers covering the NCAA women=E2=80=99s basketball =
tournament in Florida protested that state=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t=
 Say Gay=E2=80=9D bill with a moment of silence on-air.

But setting aside these few-and-far-between cases, insiders
cite a couple of reasons why the edict has been so closely observed. First,=
 some of the more opinionated talent=E2=80=94including Hill, Le Batard, and=
 Torre=E2=80=94have all left the network. And after six years in charge, th=
ere=E2=80=99s no grey area surrounding Pitaro=E2=80=99s political philosoph=
y. Everyone knows exactly what he expects of them. It=E2=80=99s a marked de=
parture from the era of John Skipper, Pitaro=E2=80=99s beloved predecessor,=
 who was professionally weaned at Rolling Stone and was much more comfortab=
le with talent sharing their opinions. Skipper encouraged an environment wh=
ere people could speak their minds, and hired people like Hill and Le Batar=
d to do just that.

Others point to the changing face of sports media, and a new era in which t=
alent like McAfee and Stephen A. have YouTube shows or podcasts to share th=
eir extracurricular opinions. Furthermore, Skipper reigned during the peak =
talent era, when ESPN was in 100 million homes. In those days,
anchors were larger-than-life stars and often had the latitude to behave th=
at way.

Now, the company is regularly culling its rolls and the surviving denizens =
in Bristol are too world-weary or chilled by the broader industrial environ=
ment to dare speak their minds=E2=80=94and subsequently contemplate a futur=
e calling a Rutgers-Northwestern game on The Big Ten Network. Yes, McAfee a=
nd Stephen A. can sort of do whatever they want, partly because they are th=
e two biggest stars left. But if Greeny, arguably Pitaro=E2=80=99s third-mo=
st-important talent, is toeing the company line=E2=80=A6 you can bet everyo=
ne else is, too.

