x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">On Wednesday mornin=
g, a few hours after the AP called the presidential election for <b>Trump</=
b>, ESPN anchor <b>Mike Greenberg</b> opened the network=E2=80=99s morning =
show, <i>Get Up</i>, with =E2=80=9Cjust one brief moment of seriousness.=E2=
=80=9D Staring at the camera with what can only be described as an <i>earne=
st</i> expression, and without mentioning either candidate, Greeny outlined=
 his view of ESPN=E2=80=99s political philosophy. =E2=80=9CIf you are choos=
ing to turn ESPN on your television today, it is because you are begging fo=
r a reprieve,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou want someone to talk about foo=
tball, which feels very normal to you. You want someone to make you laugh, =
which is what we try to do every single day. That=E2=80=99s what we=E2=80=
=99re going to do.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>When Trump won eight years ago, Bristo=
l was a political hotbed. Several ESPNers across the network decided that t=
hey
could not, and would not, remain silent. But six years into <b>Jimmy Pitaro=
=E2=80=99</b>s reign, nobody would accuse the company of being political. A=
fter Greenberg=E2=80=99s monologue, he embarked on a zany recap of the NFL=
=E2=80=99s trade deadline moves. Greenberg=E2=80=99s opening set the tone f=
or all the studio shows that followed: Even <i>First Take</i>=E2=80=99s <b>=
Stephen A. Smith</b>, who is certainly <i>not</i> shy about addressing the =
wedge issues of the day, kept his focus on the NFL. <br/><br/>In many respe=
cts, Wednesday=E2=80=99s battened-down broadcast represented the culminatio=
n of a repositioning strategy that Pitaro implemented when he was brought o=
n in the spring of 2018. Back then, the network was defined by a patina of =
activism in the post-Trump, post-<b>Kaepernick </b>#Resistance era. In 2017=
, the White House publicly called on ESPN to fire <b>Jemele</b> <b>Hill</b>=
 after the <i>SportsCenter</i> host called Trump a white supremacist on Twi=
tter. Plenty of other on-air talent, including
<b>Dan Le Batard</b> and <b>Pablo</b> <b>Torre</b>, were openly criticizing=
 Trump. <br/><br/>Pitaro wanted to wade into politics <i>only </i>when ther=
e was a clear intersection with sports, like covering athletes and coaches =
as they engaged in various political protests. Indeed, for Pitaro, the deci=
sion made business sense. He often cited research demonstrating that people=
 of <i>all </i>political persuasions would rather not hear their favorite t=
alking heads yammering about politics on ESPN. Viewers, he often tells peop=
le, see ESPN, and sports writ large, as an escape from all that. Whether th=
is is <i>actually </i>true is not a settled matter, but it=E2=80=99s undeni=
able that Pitaro lived up to his words.<br/></td>
